<dl id="n54135a"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n54" href="#n54135a">N54 (VI.B.45)</a>:  <a href="../../FF/fnbs/n54all.htm#n54135a"> 135(a)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> Jerusalemfarer <small>Orange</small></blockquote> <dd class="well"> <ul class="list-inline" id="n54135a"><li>FW 26.04 </li><li><a href="../../flex/a/lexa.htm#n54135a">2010</a> </li><li><a href="../../flex/a/l39a.htm#n54135a">1939</a> </li><li><ms href="#n54135a">MS BL 47476a-148</ms> </li><li>JJA 49:320 <a name="ad7y" href="../../FF/fdra/ada.htm#ad7y">Usage</a> </li><li> <a href="../../flex/a/ad7.htm#n54135a">Draft: I.1&sect;1.7</a>+/2.7+</li> </ul> <blockquote class="sources">There we may note the parti-coloured sail with its variegated stripes, and the rich carving of stem and stern. These magnificent sails were a source of much pride to their possessors, and the story is told of <mark>Sigurd Jerusalem-farer</mark> that on his way home from Jerusalem to Constantinople he lay for half-a-month off Cape Malea, waiting for a side wind, so that his sails might be set lengthwise along the ship and so be better seen by those standing on shore as he sailed up to Constantinople. <small> Allen Mawers, <a name="VIK2" href="../../FF/fdra/fdex.htm#VIK2"><cite title="source">The Vikings</cite></a> (1913) 100</small></blockquote> <mm class="note">Note: Sigurd the Jerusalem-farer: c. twelfth-century king of Norway. </mm> </dd></dl>
